// OS-shaped axon producer — half of the strings+numbers IPC demo.
//
// This producer simulates the *typical* OS axon payload shape, per
// Emma 2026-05-10: one input embedding (the dominant per-message
// piece) plus several scalar/string metadata fields. Most Sutra
// programs are a single classifier over an incoming embedding, with
// metadata around it. Two or three embeddings per axon would already
// be a comparatively complex program.
//
// Wire payload bundled here:
//
//   user      : string  ("alice")        — who initiated the request
//   tag       : string  ("search")       — request kind
//   priority  : int     (7)              — small bounded number
//   retries   : int     (0)              — small bounded number
//   query     : vector                   — the one LLM embedding
//
// Consumer (consumer_os.su) reads `user`, `priority`, `query`. Skips
// `tag` and `retries`. The lazy-materialization optimization (still a
// follow-on, not implemented) would prune the unread two from the
// wire at compile time.
//
// Numbers in this demo are deliberately small (single-digit / low
// hundreds). Large scalar values dominate the axon's L2 norm and can
// crosstalk into string codepoint positions, corrupting other
// fillers. A future extension can split large numbers across
// multiple synthetic axes (e.g. 4 × 16-bit chunks) so each chunk
// stays in range; for now, encode big values as multiple keyed
// entries or scale them down.
//
// Scale convention for the embedding: the embedding is multiplied by
// EMBEDDING_SCALE (= 100) before being added to the axon. Typical
// nomic-embed-text component magnitudes are ~0.03; codepoint values
// from the string fillers and the small ints sit at 7..115. Without
// scaling, the embedding's contribution to the bundle is two-to-
// three orders of magnitude smaller than the metadata's, so its
// recovered signal is below the crosstalk noise floor (cos margin
// near 0 — empirically verified). Scaling by 100 brings the
// embedding's per-component magnitude up to ~3, comparable to the
// metadata, and the recovered cosine margin against a decoy hits
// healthy positive values. Cosine is scale-invariant, so the
// consumer doesn't need to undo the multiplication — it just
// compares cosines, which the scaling improved.

function vector make_query() {
    return basis_vector("find recent files about cats");
}

function vector make_state() {
    Axon a;
    a.add("user",     "alice");
    a.add("tag",      "search");
    a.add("priority", 7);
    a.add("retries",  0);
    a.add("query",    make_query() * 100.0);
    return a;
}

function string main() {
    vector a = make_state();
    return "produced";
}
